VvisualizeVvisualize show_widgetHere's a breakdown of every design decision made:
4 actors, color-coded: Vendor (purple), Warehouse Staff (teal), Courier (coral), System Admin (amber). Color encoding makes it instantly readable — you can see at a glance which actor owns which use cases.
12 use cases across the actors:

Vendor (3): upload inventory shipment, track stock levels, view order lifecycle
Warehouse Staff (3): receive and put-away stock, reconcile inventory, assign dispatch to courier
Courier (4): view delivery list, update delivery status, capture proof of delivery, log delivery exception
Admin (2): manage users and roles, generate billing reports
System (1): auto-generate invoice — triggered via an «include» relationship, showing the automated billing that's core to OmniStore's revenue model

Why this scores high: The «include» relationship for auto-invoicing is the 3PL-specific touch — it reflects the business model (OmniStore charges per pick-and-pack/delivery automatically). "Reconcile inventory" and "Log delivery exception" directly address the critical flows named in the brief.

Ready for Deliverable 3 — API Documentation for the Courier Mobile App?yes18 MarHere is the full API Documentation for the Courier Mobile App — all 3 endpoints with complete technical specs:
  ::view-transition-group(*),
  ::view-transition-old(*),
  ::view-transition-new(*) {
    animation-duration: 0.25s;
    animation-timing-function: cubic-bezier(0.19, 1, 0.22, 1);
  }
VvisualizeVvisualize show_widgetHere's what makes this API documentation score in the 9–10 band:
Correct HTTP verbs: GET for fetching the list (read-only, no body), PATCH for partial status update (not PUT — we're only changing one field), POST for creating a new exception record. This distinction alone is a major differentiator from basic CRUD designs.
Versioning: All paths are under /v1/ via the base URL, making future API evolution backward-compatible.
422 Unprocessable on Endpoint B — this is the professional touch. A 400 means "bad syntax"; a 422 means "syntactically valid but logically impossible" (e.g., trying to move a shipment from delivered back to in_transit). This shows state-machine awareness.
Endpoint C enum values are explicit (customer_not_home | damaged_package | wrong_address | refused_delivery | other) — this means the mobile app can render a dropdown rather than a free-text field, reducing errors from couriers.
X-App-Version header on all requests allows the backend to handle older app versions gracefully during rollouts.

